Consider the regression model

\begin{align}
    \label{eqn:oildollarmodel}
    \text{Oil}_{t}= \beta_0 + \beta_1 \text{Dollar}_{t}+\epsilon_{t}
,\end{align}

\noindent where $\text{Oil}_{t}$ is the price of oil in month $t$ and
$\text{Dollar}_{t}$ is the strength of the dollar as measured by a trade
weighted index. We present estimates for the coefficients of this model in Table
\ref{tab:oildollarfit}. We tested for structural breaks in the full sample and
rejected the null hypothesis of no change, with the best estimate (according to
the CUSUM test) of the location of the change being February, 2000. When we
split the data into two sub-samples around that date, we detected no further
structural changes.

