We also estimated $\text{MA}(1)$ models for the residuals $\epsilon_{t}$ of the
model; in unreported results, we also rejected the null hypothesis of no
structural change in the $\text{MA}(1)$ model for the residuals. Additionally,
it seems that, if $\epsilon_{t}=\theta \eta_{t-1}+ \eta_t$ with
$\text{Var}(\eta_t^2) = \sigma^2$, then $\sigma$ changes in the sample, increasing around the
time of the structural change in the full sample. This suggests that the
statistic developed here could prove useful, since we may have not only
structural change in the parameters of \eqref{eqn:oildollarmodel} but also
heteroskedasticity.

In our example we will accept the CUSUM test's conclusion that a change point
occurred in the sample around February 2000 and intend to demonstrate that our
procedure would detect this change not long after it occurred.

