We attempted simulations to observe the behavior of the statistics studied in
this paper in contexts similar to what we saw in the data (although not
identical). To simulate the data for model \eqref{eqn:oildollarmodel}, we let
$\text{Dollar}_{t} - 100 \sim \operatorname{ARMA}(1, 1)$ with autocorrelation
parameter $\phi=0.985$ and moving average parameter $\theta=0.367$, with the
residuals being i.i.d. Gaussian with mean zero and variance $\sigma^2=1.323$. We
modelled the residuals with $\epsilon_{t} \sim \operatorname{MA}(1)$, with
$\theta=0.8$. The noise process for $\epsilon_t$, while always independent and
Gaussian distributed, is heteroskedastic; for $t\le 108$, the variance of the
white noise was 2, but for $t>108$ the variance was 50. We let the break point
in the simulations occur at  $t^*=122$, let  $T=130$, let the parameter vector
$\bm{\beta}=(\beta_0,\beta_1)^\top $ before the change point be
$\bm{\beta}_{0}=(41.308, -0.238)^\top $, and after the change be
$\bm{\beta}_1 = \bm{\gamma} \delta$, where $\bm{\gamma}=(329.925,
-2.809)^\top  - (41.308, -0.238)^\top $ and $\delta\in [0,2]$. Note that
$\delta=0$ corresponds to the null hypothesis of no change being true.

We should mention that while in our previous simulations we estimated long-run
variance matrices using techniques recommended in \cite{andrews91b} (using
Andrews' procedure and the quadratic spectral kernel), in this section the
statistics use the Bartlett kernel and pick the bandwidth using the procedure
recommended by \cite{lazarusetal18}. The trimming parameter for the
R\'{e}nyi-type statistics, though, is still the square root function.

We present our results in Figure \ref{fig:powerplotexample}. All statistics
exhibit size inflation when computed on the simulated data. Also, in the
simulations, it seems that the new statistic doesn't get better power than the
CUSUM statistic until $\delta>1.5$. However, the new statistic and the CUSUM
statistic both seem to suffer the least from size inflation. The R\'{e}nyi-type
statistic recommended by \cite{horvathricemiller19} sees considerable size
inflation in this context, and the Hidalgo-Seo statistic is the most inflated of
them all. We do note that the new procedure exhibits power, though, along with
the other procedures. Additionally, we observed similar size inflation for $T$
closer to $t^{*}$.

As stated above, our goal is to demonstrate that the new procedure could detect
a structural change soon after it occurred in the sample. To do so, we employed
a procedure like that used in \cite{horvathricemiller19}. We considered an
expanding window of data, where the left end point of the window was fixed at
January 1990 and the right end point moved forward in time, adding additional
months to the sample. We wish to see when each statistic would start rejecting
the null hypothesis of no change.

