We present our results in Figure \ref{fig:oildollarexpandingwindow}. While the
simulations suggested that size inflation could be a problem, this does not
appear to be the case in the actual data except for the two statistics that
experienced the most size inflation. The CUSUM statistic does not reject the
null hypothesis in the observed region, the Hidalgo-Seo statistic always does,
the original R\'{e}nyi-type statistic sometimes does not and sometimes does, and
the new version of the R\'{e}nyi-type statistic gradually goes from not
rejecting the null hypothesis to rejecting at the end of the window in a
visually linear manner, and thus seems the most well-behaved of the statistics
considered here.

We admit that the simulation results presented in Figure
\ref{fig:powerplotexample} cast doubt on the validity of our conclusions made in
the above paragraph. We could have been lucky in observing a reasonable pattern
in the data. However, it is possible that some of the features that appeared in
simulated data were not as big an issue as they were in the real data; the
statistical features we simulated may have been a rough approximation of the
real data's features. In any case, the size inflation seen in the simulations
may have been overstated in absolute terms, but the relative size inflation may
be meaningful.

